		<section id="author-box">
			<div class="block-head">
				<h3>About Major Click </h3>
			</div>
			<div class="post-listing">
					<div class="author-avatar">
		<img alt='Major Click' src='http://aattp.org/wp-content/uploads/2013/09/Major-Click_avatar_1380235784-75x75.jpg' class='avatar avatar-75 photo' height='75' width='75' />	</div><!-- #author-avatar -->
			<div class="author-description">
			Major R. Click is a founding member of Click. McGhee, serving as the firm's president and CEO. This Birmingham native hails from a diverse background and has a proven track record as a leader. His long history of working behind the scenes in an effort to get things done speaks for itself. Major and the Click. McGhee are primed and positioned to get things done.
Major was called into politics at an early age. After his sixteenth birthday, Major began working for prominent criminal defense attorney, the late David Cromwell Johnson, who was representing former Alabama Governor, Jim Folsom.  As Johnson’s assistant, this “early bloomer” quickly realized that he had found his passion, leading him to pursue a career in public service.
While obtaining his degree in Political Science at the University of South Alabama, Major was selected to work in Washington DC as a Congressional Intern for U.S. Representative, Earl Hilliard. Following his internship, Major went to work for Governor Don Siegelman, supporting his efforts to bring an education lottery to the state of Alabama.
After working for Siegelman, Major worked tirelessly in an effort to assist former Alabama Court of Civil Appeals Judge, Sharon Yates, in her bid for the state’s top judicial post of Chief Justice. After graduation, he devoted himself for two years, to the Alabama Democratic Senate Caucus, working as their Finance Director.  
In 2004, Major was presented with an opportunity he could not refuse resulting in his return to our nation’s capital to work for the Democratic National Committee (DNC) in and effort to elect the Kerry-Edwards ticket. Upon his return to Birmingham in 2005, Major worked with the Retirement Systems of Alabama (RSA), Ross Bridge Resort. While working for RSA, he quickly excelled in areas of public relations and marketing.
In 2007, Major was hired as a federal contractor for the department of Housing and Economic Development (HUD). Throughout his three-year contract with HUD, Major specialized in helping turn distressed properties into communities for low-income families to call home. After the contract ended, Affordable Housing continue to be an area of special interest for Major.
In the 2010 election cycle, Major worked with various progressive candidates throughout the state in an effort to create a better Alabama. During this time, he was recruited by Summit Housing Partners to serve as a Regional Portfolio Manager. His position entailed working with Section 8 and tax credit properties in order to facilitate expanded access and affordable housing to more Alabamians. 
Following his contract with Summit, Major worked with Jefferson County, Judge Bob Vance, in an effort to help defeat, the once removed, Chief Justice Roy Moore. Most recently, Major worked with the City of Birmingham Economic Development department, working to retain and attract new business to the “Magic City”. As a native of the city, Major truly sees the magic in the city and in her people.

Clearly a man with a track record in politics, Major understands the landscape as well as the players, making him an asset to any candidate, cause or interest. His political background, combined with his experience in marketing, PR and economic development will enable Major to be an asset to all of those he serves. His experience, wisdom and charismatic style position him to play a diplomatic role in facilitating positive change within today's increasingly challenging environment.
When Major is not working, he can also be seen on Birmingham View, Wednesday mornings at 6:30 on UPN 68, offering political analysis and insight into issues affecting our city, state, and nation. He enjoys reading, sports (especially his beloved Crimson Tide), thoroughbred racing, current events,  live jazz ,cigars, history, museums and travel.		</div><!-- #author-description -->
		
