			<div class="author-comment">
				<cite class="fn">Disabled Widow with Teenage Son on SNAP</cite> 				<div class="comment-meta commentmetadata"><a href="http://aattp.org/panera-bread-ceo-learns-poverty-firsthand-week-poverty/#comment-130514">	October 2, 2013 at 11:36 am</a></div><!-- .comment-meta .commentmetadata -->
			</div>
			<div class="clear"></div>
			<div class="comment-content">
									
				<p>OMG&#8230;  Here&#8217;s a little dose of reality for everyone.  I am a disabled widow with an autistic 15.5 year old son.  I am not able to collect the widow&#8217;s benefit from my deceased husband&#8217;s social security until I am fifty years old which is many years away.  My son loses his father&#8217;s social security benefit when he turns 16.  Why are we both out of luck?  Because that&#8217;s the way it is.  My husband committed suicide, so there were no death benefits for us from his job, either.  Our SNAP benefits are $200 per month.  I do without for myself because my teenaged son eats everything&#8230;  I am able to eat one meal a day.  Usually it&#8217;s so high in sodium and low in protein that I am surprised I am still alive. Organic food?  Fresh vegetables and fruit?  We can&#8217;t afford them. I understand that SNAP benefits are supposed to &#8220;supplement&#8221; my disability income, after I pay for my medicare, I get $822 a month for EVERYTHING else.  We live in a large city because that&#8217;s we don&#8217;t have enough to move to a smaller city that may or may not be a better value.  We have a crazy, yes, I said crazy, Republican governor who turned down millions to secure the state health care fund, he dismantled collective bargaining for unions, and he is trying to privatize every entity of government he can get away with because he has &#8220;political aspirations&#8221; that go beyond this state.  The man is delusional, but he&#8217;s working his way up in his mind.  The job he had before he became the governor?  He dismantled the mental health system.  Not coincidental, but, that&#8217;s the reason my severely depressed and suicidal husband was only committed for 5 days total after a severe overdose where I had to resuscitate him as the paramedics that my ten year old son had to call and bring up to where I was doing CPR on him.  That was his third attempt in a month.  There was a court hearing where I testified for his committal and he was back in our home five days later.  One month later he was dead.  He did it at work in front of all of his colleagues who were MD&#8217;s.  Even they couldn&#8217;t save him.</p>
<p>Now, try to think again about berating the people who receive those &#8220;handouts&#8221; of SNAP benefits.  I WISH we got $4.50 a day for each of us.  I am horrified that these out of touch with the &#8220;common&#8221; folk politicians and CEO&#8217;s have so much control over the minds of the tax paying sheeple that are seeing their agenda as the right way to go.  </p>
<p>I wish we could afford to eat at Panera.  He just got some really great publicity for his huge corporation. *clap* *clap*  Way to go!  How about handing out some free meal coupons for all the SNAP recipients in this country?  You can afford it!  It&#8217;s more free publicity, and I&#8217;m sure it would be a great write off!  I&#8217;ll be expecting ours in the mail!  That would actually help everyone!</p>
<p>ok, down off of the soapbox&#8230;</p>
