	<li id="comment-129465">
		<div  class="comment odd alt thread-odd thread-alt depth-1 comment-wrap" >
			<div class="comment-avatar"><img alt='' src='http://i1.wp.com/graph.facebook.com/1313782668/picture?q=type%3Dlarge%26_md5%3D0205457e5edfacde62bee774e48200d1&#038;resize=45%2C45' class='avatar avatar-45 photo' height='45' width='45' /></div>
			<div class="author-comment">
				<cite class="fn"><a href='https://www.facebook.com/bunguskafungus' rel='external nofollow' class='url'>Mike Talbott</a></cite> 				<div class="comment-meta commentmetadata"><a href="http://aattp.org/panera-bread-ceo-learns-poverty-firsthand-week-poverty/#comment-129465">	September 28, 2013 at 3:35 pm</a></div><!-- .comment-meta .commentmetadata -->
			</div>
			<div class="clear"></div>
			<div class="comment-content">
									
				<p>I like it when people that have been over privileged for so long take a step back to see how the rest of us are doing. You can argue the politics of giving out snap all you want but until you have experienced it for yourself your point will most likely be invalid. The amount of people that are jobless, homeless and/ or disabled in this country is mind blowing, and the statistics aren&#8217;t an accurate representation. They only count what they can see, and the truth is the people living at the bottom often times cant afford to be seen. I have heard over privileged arguments saying things like &#8220;those people put themselves in that  position&#8221; or &#8220;they are just lazy&#8221;. Do you know how much actual physical work happens for minimum wage or less than minimum wage? the reason they pay so little is because the work is so hard but they know they have a mile long line of replacements when you cant do it anymore. The higher people in this country get paid the less physically demanding the jobs become, but on the same coin the more mentally demanding. This is why you see more CEO&#8217;s and business people going to psychologists and more poor workers getting physically injured and going to the hospital. When a CEO goes to a shrink, their medical insurance provides for it, when a worker goes to the ER (probably with no medical insurance because rarely do min wage jobs give you anything other than min wage) L&amp;I might pay for it but most likely they are left with a huge bill and no job. So they are left with govt. subsidies to live off of until they heal, if they heal. And if they don&#8217;t they are disabled. The job that they were working is now filed with another worker that will eventually hurt themselves and join the ranks of the disabled. I&#8217;m sure someone is going to comment about how i left something out, or misspelled something or they are going to try to denounce my claim, to you go f*** yourself. This is what happens here, where i live, I see it everyday in the food bank line. Sure there are drug addicts and drunks and lazy people everywhere that alter your perception. They are the ones you see. But the same people live in the middle and the top as well and you don&#8217;t complain when they get tax write offs and bailouts do you?</p>
			</div>
			<div class="reply"><a class='comment-reply-link' href='/panera-bread-ceo-learns-poverty-firsthand-week-poverty/?replytocom=129465#respond' onclick='return addComment.moveForm("comment-129465", "129465", "respond", "16180")'>Reply</a></div><!-- .reply -->
