			<div class="comment-avatar"><img alt='' src='http://0.gravatar.com/avatar/a70a9863c414db4b97c7833ffa448acf?s=45&amp;d=identicon&amp;r=G' class='avatar avatar-45 photo' height='45' width='45' /></div>
			<div class="author-comment">
				<cite class="fn">Twyla</cite> 				<div class="comment-meta commentmetadata"><a href="http://aattp.org/panera-bread-ceo-learns-poverty-firsthand-week-poverty/#comment-129423">	September 28, 2013 at 12:06 pm</a></div><!-- .comment-meta .commentmetadata -->
			</div>
			<div class="clear"></div>
			<div class="comment-content">
									
				<p>Experience has shown that the more money you have, the more money you spend!  Hence the lottery winners who 5 years later are broke again!  It&#8217;s actually harder for me now that I&#8217;m earning a decent living than it was when I was a broke college kid.  Why? Because before I knew any better, I spent everything I made!  People were always telling me I should make a budget and follow it, but no one taught me HOW!!  Increasing SNAP benefits and raising minimum wage will help those in need ONLY if it is coupled with intense money management training and assistance with making a monthly budget.  This instruction should be required ongoing learning beginning no later than the freshman year of high school. Too many kids drop out or even graduate with no idea how to balance a checkbook, much less how to make and stick to spending on a budget.<br />
If minimum wage is increased to a living wage, and SNAP benefits are increased without money management training, people will have more money but will still be broke all the time!!</p>
			</div>
