			<div class="comment-content">
									
				<p>I worked for Panera Bread as a manager. Reviews were given to associated twice a year, although raises were handed out once a year.  The cafe was busy, it was staffed at over 50 associates.  When it came time for raises, the cafe had $3.40 to disperse amongst the associates.  Eliminating those that may have had performance  issues, or those that were new, that was $3.40 to be split amongst 40 associates.  If you haven&#8217;t already done the math, that isn&#8217;t even .09 cents an hour.  So when an associate would come up to me and say I&#8217;m hungry, yes I fed that person.  There are boxes at the counter to contribute to the Feed America, but I think we have an obligation to take care of our own before we try to reach out on a broadar note.  And as a reminder Panera Bread, in many areas is corporate which means they are all about the bottom line.  And although they are generous with those organizations that they support, little thought is given if presented with helping others.  I attempted to get approved to participate in the Toys for Tots program this Christmas, and was turned down.  Silly me, I thought what a great charity to be paired with especially to help kids.  That was the deciding factor for me, and I am now with an organization that with participate in the Toys for Tots program  this Christmas and has encouraged me to share my ideas to give back with the other managers.  You won&#8217;t see it in the newspapers, tv, or internet&#8230;&#8230;that&#8217;s the difference when things are done for the right reason&#8230;&#8230;..</p>
