			<div class="comment-content">
									
				<p>I gave each of  my children, ages 20 and 22, $200  per month for purchasing food while they were living without food plans in college. I explained to them I would give them the same amount in cash as a single person gets for food stamps in our county. Both children were able to feed themselves with healthy food choices as they became careful shoppers. Sometimes their choices for variety was quite limited, but neither child bought processed or prepared foods which tend to be costly. Both children also shopped at discount grocery stores and taking advantages of sales and coupons.</p>
