	<li id="comment-129838">
		<div  class="comment odd alt depth-2 comment-wrap" >
			<div class="comment-avatar"><img alt='' src='http://0.gravatar.com/avatar/6e2396ce05bf049218c226f9d570ab9b?s=45&amp;d=identicon&amp;r=G' class='avatar avatar-45 photo' height='45' width='45' /></div>
			<div class="author-comment">
				<cite class="fn">Bill Wallace</cite> 				<div class="comment-meta commentmetadata"><a href="http://aattp.org/panera-bread-ceo-learns-poverty-firsthand-week-poverty/#comment-129838">	September 29, 2013 at 6:28 pm</a></div><!-- .comment-meta .commentmetadata -->
			</div>
			<div class="clear"></div>
			<div class="comment-content">
									
				<p>Larry You are wrong on several fronts. If you get SNAP, the entire amount is loaded onto the card at the beginning of the month. There is nothing that stops you from investing in staples or making good choices when ingredients are on sale. Not having a freezer might limit you some in prebuying perishables, but you can adapt.</p>
<p>Secondly, Note that a family of 3 receives a maximum benefit of $526 per month or $17.50 per day. A single person gets $ 200 or $6.60 per day<br />
<a href="https://www.azdes.gov/main.aspx?menu=355&#038;id=5202" rel="nofollow">https://www.azdes.gov/main.aspx?menu=355&#038;id=5202</a> shows the AZ numbers.</p>
<p>According to the USDA, the average per person benefit is about $ 134 per month or $ 4.65 per day although single people get less. This works out to $14.00 per day for a family of 3.<br />
<a href="http://www.fns.usda.gov/pd/18SNAPavg$PP.htm" rel="nofollow">http://www.fns.usda.gov/pd/18SNAPavg$PP.htm</a> for averages.</p>
<p>If you can&#8217;t feed your 3 person family on $17.40 per day ($526 / month), then you are doing something wrong. You must be eating frozen prepared food, expensive meat, soda, junk food, wasting food or buying national brands rather than the same store brand foods at half the cost. This is my food budget and I meet it every month (usually under), although I don&#8217;t include beer or wine since that is not SNAP eligible anyway. We eat good food in balanced meals because I cook from ingredients, not packages. I use a different recipe every day</p>
<p>And I hear a lot of &#8220;I can&#8217;t&#8221; whining. Most of the rest of the world cooks nutritious meals on 1 or 2 burners and doesn&#8217;t have fridges. They don&#8217;t complain, they cook. They couldn&#8217;t get fresh meat in Hawaii during WW II, but they could get Spam. But they didn&#8217;t complain, they created a cuisine based on Spam that is still popular today. Work with the food that you can get and create good food using the tools that you have.</p>
			</div>
			<div class="reply"><a class='comment-reply-link' href='/panera-bread-ceo-learns-poverty-firsthand-week-poverty/?replytocom=129838#respond' onclick='return addComment.moveForm("comment-129838", "129838", "respond", "16180")'>Reply</a></div><!-- .reply -->
		</div><!-- #comment-##  -->

