	<li id="comment-129872">
		<div  class="comment byuser comment-author-richard-rowe even depth-3 comment-wrap" >
			<div class="comment-avatar"><img alt='Richard Rowe' src='http://aattp.org/wp-content/uploads/2013/09/Richard-Rowe_avatar_1378515340-45x45.jpg' class='avatar avatar-45 photo' height='45' width='45' /></div>
			<div class="author-comment">
				<cite class="fn">Richard Rowe</cite> 				<div class="comment-meta commentmetadata"><a href="http://aattp.org/panera-bread-ceo-learns-poverty-firsthand-week-poverty/#comment-129872">	September 29, 2013 at 8:01 pm</a></div><!-- .comment-meta .commentmetadata -->
			</div>
			<div class="clear"></div>
			<div class="comment-content">
									
				<p>Bill&#8230;WE GET IT. WE GET IT. You are the spirit of Martha Stewart, wrapped in the shell of Emeril Lagasse, basted liberally with Coupon Queen. Yes, we ALL understand at this point that you&#8217;ve got plenty of time to cook from three grains of flour and seven pounds of rutebegas you traded some old tin cans for. WE GET IT. You&#8217;ve got the energy of a nuclear reactor, the creativity of H.P. Lovecraft, and you probably suspend cannonballs from your testicles in the snow just to harden your resolve to grow your own corn from seed so you can feed it to chickens to make eggs for feed to give your cow so you can butcher it at the end of the year and save 12 cents a pound on beef. WE. GET. IT. </p>
<p>Now the WE. GET. YOU., I would ask that you get it through your head that not everybody is you. Not everybody knows how to cook anything that doesn&#8217;t go in a microwave, nor do they have the time or energy to learn. Some people are single parents chasing three kids around, they&#8217;re old, physically or mentally disabled, living in motel rooms, selling their food stamps to pay the electric bill, or any number of a hundred other reasons that they can&#8217;t do all the shit you you. Or maybe they just WON&#8217;T. Maybe they could hypothetically learn to cook, or find the time, sleep an hour less a night so they have time to clean the kitchen afterward, pay for the extra electricity to run that oven and two burners, or keep the cockroaches off their counters long enough to cook anything&#8230;WHATEVER. But they don&#8217;t, and they&#8217;re not. </p>
<p>The minute you&#8217;d like to institute a social welfare program to teach people Home Ec and time management skills so they can eat organically grown filet mignon paninis on the money you spend on chicken feed, then go right the Hell ahead. You&#8217;re obviously an amazing individual, and everyone could learn from your wisdom. Or maybe you&#8217;re just average, and everyone else is a piece of shit.</p>
<p>The point isn&#8217;t what you can or can&#8217;t do in YOUR PARTICULAR SITUATION, with YOUR particular set of skills, with the time and energy at YOUR disposal, or how YOU have a fresh fish market down the street that sells salmon for 9 cents a pound off on Wednesdays. The point is what&#8217;s actually HAPPENING. In the Real World. For the rest of humanity. That&#8217;s the reality that needs to be dealt with, however it gets dealt with. If you have a problem with what&#8217;s being sold, then write a letter to the FDA. Write a letter to the Board of Education. Start a damned movement, or a petition to make everyone as wonderful and wise as you. </p>
<p>But until then, open your damned eyes and look what&#8217;s really happening. People are going hungry. For whatever reason, whoever&#8217;s to blame, that&#8217;s what&#8217;s happening. And until your social and educational programs, and FDA reforms, kick in, I&#8217;m afraid the only real solution is to just give them more goddamned money.</p>
			</div>
