			</div>
			<div class="clear"></div>
			<div class="comment-content">
									
				<p>Bill, you need to get real. I was receiving SNAP benefits for awhile, to the tune of $146 a month. Yes, it&#8217;s loaded onto a card on a specific date each month (which day depends on your county ID number). That money helped me to provide nutritious meals for my 2 kids. I am in a wheelchair and receive SSDI. I was at Mayo Clinic for a month and while I was there, I got a letter from the county saying I had to pay back all the SNAP benefits I&#8217;d received because the county had failed to count my miniscule child support (though I&#8217;d reported it many times). That little amount pushed me over the income limit. Now I REALLY struggle to make ends meet. By the last week of the month, we are eating store brand mac and cheese and canned vegetables. Fresh fruit and veggies are never in the budget &#8211; they just cost too much. Frozen costs too much, too. So canned fruits and veggies are all I can afford. Meat is a luxury, given twice a week. Peanut butter and beans make up the protein deficiency in our diets. Milk is outrageously expensive, so we rarely get that &#8211; or cheese, for that matter. My kids are teenagers, one of whom is autistic (so he cannot work to help bring in much-needed money), and they need a lot of food for their growing bodies. As a mother, it is devastating to realize that I cannot provide the kinds of meals they should be getting. I can&#8217;t cook up a storm, as you apparently do, either. Why? because I am in a wheelchair, and only have one good hand. I&#8217;ve gotten 3rd degree burns on my thighs from spilling a pan of spaghetti sauce on it. That was a fun day (dripping sarcasm). I am the face of the poor in America. And you can bet your bottom dollar that the county is never going to get that money back from me. I don&#8217;t have a single penny to spare, especially  now that I don&#8217;t even have that little bit of help to keep my head above water. Additionally, because I no longer receive SNAP benefits, my kids no longer qualify for free lunch, only reduced-priced lunches &#8211; another expense I have to come up with &#8211; because at least at school I know they will get fresh fruit and veggies. But it often means I cannot go to doctor appointments since the trade-off is gas money for the van. You need to seriously close your mouth. You don&#8217;t have a clue what life is like for those of us who live on the bottom. But congrats on being Mister Freaking Fabulous. How nice it must be to live in your world.</p>
			</div>
