	<li id="comment-129361">
		<div  class="comment odd alt depth-4 comment-wrap" >
			<div class="comment-avatar"><img alt='' src='http://1.gravatar.com/avatar/1c3273cd41ce7ac467ae839cbbc6836e?s=45&amp;d=identicon&amp;r=G' class='avatar avatar-45 photo' height='45' width='45' /></div>
			<div class="author-comment">
				<cite class="fn">The Laurax</cite> 				<div class="comment-meta commentmetadata"><a href="http://aattp.org/panera-bread-ceo-learns-poverty-firsthand-week-poverty/#comment-129361">	September 28, 2013 at 4:55 am</a></div><!-- .comment-meta .commentmetadata -->
			</div>
			<div class="clear"></div>
			<div class="comment-content">
									
				<p>Yes, that&#8217;s what Realredread was referring to&#8211;the stereotypes. And s/he is referring to those two categories as if they are mutually exclusive, rather than being one and the same. It&#8217;s the same mentality behind John McCaine saying of Obama, &#8220;He&#8217;s not a Muslim, he&#8217;s a good guy,&#8221; as if &#8220;Muslim&#8221; and &#8220;good guy&#8221; are two different things, and not one and the same. </p>
<p>Take a look at these two statements and see what I mean:</p>
<p>&#8220;It isn&#8217;t just blacks on welfare, there are elderly on the program and vets.&#8221;</p>
<p>Translation: It&#8217;s not just those other people that you think are on welfare, there are people like the elderly and vets on it as well.</p>
<p>&#8220;He&#8217;s not a Muslim, he&#8217;s a good guy.&#8221;</p>
<p>Translation: He&#8217;s not one of those other people, he&#8217;s a good guy.</p>
<p>Btw, for the record, I STRONGLY support not only maintaining but EXPANDING the food stamps program, and I&#8217;m glad to put my money behind that. So believe me, I&#8217;m not looking to attack Realredread, since we absolutely agree on this issue. I just had to point out that there was an underlying, implicit racial bias in that statement. I know it was completely unintentional, but it was there, and it had to be called out because otherwise it simply reinforces another stereotype (not that black people are on welfare, but that they are the &#8220;other&#8221;) even more.</p>
			</div>
