				<p>Jessica perhaps you should heed your own advice. I agree fully with Mark. I was on Welfare years ago as a single Mom. I saw first hand the abuse of the system. You are wrong that only the elderly and disabled use energy assistance I saw lots of people abuse the system letting their energy bills go unpaid and pocketing the money so they can get shut off notices so HEAP would pay the bill. &#8220;Most don&#8217;t live in HUD housing&#8221; Really?? That&#8217;s only because the waiting list is usually 2 yrs. or more. Mark is right the lower middle class are the forgotten people as are small business owners. My son and his wife both work so they don&#8217;t qualify for anything. They barely get by but they don&#8217;t qualify for head start for their child. They were told they&#8217;d have to pay $200.00 a month. I worked in an ER and saw a small business owner who had a broken leg leave the ER in a splint because he said he couldn&#8217;t afford the surgery to properly fix his leg yet an illegal farm worker fractured his neck and we the taxpayers footed the $500,000.00 bill for his care. You say that at least ONE member of a SNAP household is working like that is ok? If you can&#8217;t feed your family shouldn&#8217;t everyone who is able-bodied and of age be working? One last thing when I became disabled last year they sent me a form that I could get a free phone and they sent a duplicate form and said to pass it on to a friend. Seriously??? I have a cheap cell phone and pay my own bills. You can get on Consumer Cellular and get a phone for &#8220;emergencies&#8221; for $10.00 a month. The system is broken and needs to be fixed. Help those that truly need help but the able-bodied need to get a job and pull their own weight.</p>
