	<li id="comment-129395">
		<div  class="comment even depth-4 comment-wrap" >
			<div class="comment-avatar"><img alt='' src='http://1.gravatar.com/avatar/16d1e3c9221edbec82cd003b294555d8?s=45&amp;d=identicon&amp;r=G' class='avatar avatar-45 photo' height='45' width='45' /></div>
			<div class="author-comment">
				<cite class="fn"><a href='https://www.facebook.com/mig.crowe' rel='external nofollow' class='url'>Mira52</a></cite> 				<div class="comment-meta commentmetadata"><a href="http://aattp.org/panera-bread-ceo-learns-poverty-firsthand-week-poverty/#comment-129395">	September 28, 2013 at 9:07 am</a></div><!-- .comment-meta .commentmetadata -->
			</div>
			<div class="clear"></div>
			<div class="comment-content">
									
				<p>The Salvation Army may not pay a lot to their General, but they do own the housing she lives in for free and they pay all the utilities and taxes; and they own the car she uses, and they give them a stipend for food and other things.  When you add that all up, they do pretty darn good.</p>
<p>And they are not always there to help out.  In our area I have yet to see them at local disasters (I have been working disaster services for 30 years).  If someone needs something they have, it has to be paid for.  It is not given out for free.</p>
<p>And the only folks who go out to fires and search and rescues with food and coffee for the victims and fire/police/EMS is the Red Cross.  They don&#8217;t charge for this.  They just do it.</p>
<p>And put a family who has lost their home up for several nights at a motel until they can make other arrangements to get back on their feet.  They also give them debit cards with funds on it based on their needs so they can get clothing.  And it is not a loan.  It does not have to be paid back.</p>
			</div>
			<div class="reply"><a class='comment-reply-link' href='/panera-bread-ceo-learns-poverty-firsthand-week-poverty/?replytocom=129395#respond' onclick='return addComment.moveForm("comment-129395", "129395", "respond", "16180")'>Reply</a></div><!-- .reply -->
