	<ul class="children">
	<li id="comment-129192">
		<div  class="comment even depth-4 comment-wrap" >
			<div class="comment-avatar"><img alt='' src='http://0.gravatar.com/avatar/6e2396ce05bf049218c226f9d570ab9b?s=45&amp;d=identicon&amp;r=G' class='avatar avatar-45 photo' height='45' width='45' /></div>
			<div class="author-comment">
				<cite class="fn">Bill Wallace</cite> 				<div class="comment-meta commentmetadata"><a href="http://aattp.org/panera-bread-ceo-learns-poverty-firsthand-week-poverty/#comment-129192">	September 27, 2013 at 3:50 pm</a></div><!-- .comment-meta .commentmetadata -->
			</div>
			<div class="clear"></div>
			<div class="comment-content">
									
				<p>I live in Arizona. </p>
<p>One gallon of milk is regularly priced at $2.59 per gallon but I got it on sale. When they mark meat down at my grocery, all they do is slap a mark down sticker on it. The original package is never disturbed. They usually mark it down 2 days before the &#8220;sell by date&#8221; which is long before the meat will spoil. They refuse to sell any meat that is even close to bad here and if it is off, they will refund you without question. I have watched them markdown the meat.</p>
<p>Salmon is generally readily available at markdown and then it does cost the same as decent ground beef..I think that they have a hard time selling at full price in this economy, but they do need to stock it.</p>
<p>I always use frozen spinach to cook with at $1.00 per 10 oz packet unless I am making a wilted spinach dish or a salad where fresh spinach is necessary. I always buy store brand because it is the same stuff without the cost of brand name and advertising. </p>
<p>The cheap extruded beef in the plastic tube is gross and I never use it. Our regular ground beef runs $3.99 / lb for the grease laden 70/30 stuff and $4.99 / lb for good meat. Coincidentally, they had petite sirloin steaks on sale today for &#8220;buy 1 pack get 2 free&#8221; for $8.99 / lb. That works out to $3.00 / lb for steak. Would you rather eat steak or nasty ground beef that costs more per pound.</p>
<p>Food City run by Bashes is the supermarket in our poorer areas, although they also exist throughout the city. It has the same food selection as my market with additions that reflect food preferences in the neighborhood. They have Nopales and cactus pears, tripe, bulk 50 lb rice and beans, fresh tortillas and the best Chorizo. Their prices are similar to ours. I can&#8217;t get these items in my local store. I can&#8217;t say what other cities groceries are like, but I have shopped at Food City because I used to work near one..</p>
			</div>
			<div class="reply"><a class='comment-reply-link' href='/panera-bread-ceo-learns-poverty-firsthand-week-poverty/?replytocom=129192#respond' onclick='return addComment.moveForm("comment-129192", "129192", "respond", "16180")'>Reply</a></div><!-- .reply -->
