	<ul class="children">
	<li id="comment-129247">
		<div  class="comment odd alt depth-5 comment-wrap" >
			<div class="comment-avatar"><img alt='' src='http://1.gravatar.com/avatar/37e7c2bd57a1ab9ab6ed89428b94fc28?s=45&amp;d=identicon&amp;r=G' class='avatar avatar-45 photo' height='45' width='45' /></div>
			<div class="author-comment">
				<cite class="fn"><a href='http://babble' rel='external nofollow' class='url'>Eve</a></cite> 				<div class="comment-meta commentmetadata"><a href="http://aattp.org/panera-bread-ceo-learns-poverty-firsthand-week-poverty/#comment-129247">	September 27, 2013 at 8:04 pm</a></div><!-- .comment-meta .commentmetadata -->
			</div>
			<div class="clear"></div>
			<div class="comment-content">
									
				<p>Bill, with all due respect, I don&#8217;t know where you get your numbers.  When all of the government automatic budget cuts went into effect, my hours were cut suddenly and drastically.  We had to file for SNAP benefits.  Our monthly allotment for 5 people was 420.00 this means that we have 84 dollars a month per person, roughly 2.80 per day or .93 per meal per person.  So a meal that costs 2.23 per serving exceeds the meal budget per person by  1.30 cents per person.  That is a meal and a half over budget per person.  Using this as a sample budget meal would lead to a cost of 33.45 a day to feed my family &#8230;.on a budget of 13.95 from SNAP.  If I did that my benefits would be exhausted in only 12.5 days.  My family lives mostly on oatmeal, rice, beans, veggies from our garden and sale items.  We still run out of benefits about a week before the month ends.  Now we aren&#8217;t complaining. We aren&#8217;t meant to live on this only to get by in short hard times but no one should suggest it is an easy free ride or some bonanza.  It is terribly difficult especially if you have no food preparation knowledge to speak of or work two jobs and have no time to prepare food as, contrary to popular belief, many recipients do.  We should all find a way to help those with benefits fare better when they must lean on them and have more compassion and make fewer assumptions about their character.</p>
			</div>
			<div class="reply"></div><!-- .reply -->
		</div><!-- #comment-##  -->

