	<li id="comment-129171">
		<div  class="comment even depth-2 comment-wrap" >
			<div class="comment-avatar"><img alt='' src='http://0.gravatar.com/avatar/6e2396ce05bf049218c226f9d570ab9b?s=45&amp;d=identicon&amp;r=G' class='avatar avatar-45 photo' height='45' width='45' /></div>
			<div class="author-comment">
				<cite class="fn">Bill Wallace</cite> 				<div class="comment-meta commentmetadata"><a href="http://aattp.org/panera-bread-ceo-learns-poverty-firsthand-week-poverty/#comment-129171">	September 27, 2013 at 12:59 pm</a></div><!-- .comment-meta .commentmetadata -->
			</div>
			<div class="clear"></div>
			<div class="comment-content">
									
				<p>I generally shop at the neighborhood Fry&#8217;s supermarket. It&#8217;s smaller than the other grocery stores in our area, but it has a better meat department. Usually I drive a car to it for large shopping trips, but it is close enough to ride a bike to easily. My son walks up there regularly with his friends.</p>
<p>I just watch the sales and buy when it is cheap and use my freezer. I generally buy standard size packages of my ingredients. I change the menu to suit what is on sale or what I have in the house. I buy bagged spices for $0.89 to $1.09 per bag and reuse my bottles. Buying in the bottle adds $3.00 or more to the price of any spice. While it is not good for sandwiches, the $1.00 per loaf bread is perfect to make bread crumbs and croutons. Good day old bread works for other uses. I do have a breadmaker, but I know that most people don&#8217;t have one.</p>
<p>My daughter works at a general merchandise store where olive oil is $7.99 per liter less her 20% discount. Olive oil never spoils, but is usually available discounted somewhere. But you could have made the green beans using regular cheap veggie oil if you couldn&#8217;t get a good price on olive oil. </p>
<p>I also repurpose heavily. A whole chicken makes a great roast followed by soup or stew made with the carcass. Even a store bought rotisserie chicken can be used this way to make 2 or more meals. You throw away a meal when you toss the carcass.</p>
<p>I do plan ahead, but if I am at the end of the week&#8217;s budget, I will not buy a staple item and just modify my menu to use what I have. I do think that in this era of prepacked convenience cooking that many people don&#8217;t have the cooking skills that are needed to create these meals from basic ingredients. Premade frozen foods also destroy the budget.</p>
			</div>
			<div class="reply"><a class='comment-reply-link' href='/panera-bread-ceo-learns-poverty-firsthand-week-poverty/?replytocom=129171#respond' onclick='return addComment.moveForm("comment-129171", "129171", "respond", "16180")'>Reply</a></div><!-- .reply -->
		</div><!-- #comment-##  -->

	<ul class="children">
	<li id="comment-129306">
		<div  class="comment odd alt depth-3 comment-wrap" >
			<div class="comment-avatar"><img alt='' src='http://0.gravatar.com/avatar/ce9c9708663157c793902f987dac4fec?s=45&amp;d=identicon&amp;r=G' class='avatar avatar-45 photo' height='45' width='45' /></div>
			<div class="author-comment">
				<cite class="fn">jsb16</cite> 				<div class="comment-meta commentmetadata"><a href="http://aattp.org/panera-bread-ceo-learns-poverty-firsthand-week-poverty/#comment-129306">	September 27, 2013 at 11:34 pm</a></div><!-- .comment-meta .commentmetadata -->
			</div>
			<div class="clear"></div>
			<div class="comment-content">
									
				<p>Having a working freezer/fridge/oven/range/car is not guaranteed in the US. Heck, even a working roof isn&#8217;t guaranteed. Without a working freezer, buying in bulk is somewhere between impractical and impossible. Without a working oven/range, cooking is somewhere between impractical and impossible. (Have you ever tried cooking a whole chicken on a hot plate? It may be possible, but it&#8217;s not simple.) Without a working car, chances are you&#8217;re spending an hour or so commuting, which makes preparing meals from scratch somewhere between impractical and impossible. Also, without a working car, chances are you&#8217;re out of range of decent supermarkets.</p>
<p>One of the ironies of US economics is that you need to have a certain amount of economic stability in order to eat cheaply.</p>
			</div>
			<div class="reply"><a class='comment-reply-link' href='/panera-bread-ceo-learns-poverty-firsthand-week-poverty/?replytocom=129306#respond' onclick='return addComment.moveForm("comment-129306", "129306", "respond", "16180")'>Reply</a></div><!-- .reply -->
