	<li id="comment-129023">
		<div  class="comment odd alt thread-odd thread-alt depth-1 comment-wrap" >
			<div class="comment-avatar"><img alt='' src='http://0.gravatar.com/avatar/e9097a2e69b0d662cfdfa45281e168b6?s=45&amp;d=identicon&amp;r=G' class='avatar avatar-45 photo' height='45' width='45' /></div>
			<div class="author-comment">
				<cite class="fn">Glen Davis</cite> 				<div class="comment-meta commentmetadata"><a href="http://aattp.org/panera-bread-ceo-learns-poverty-firsthand-week-poverty/#comment-129023">	September 26, 2013 at 8:25 pm</a></div><!-- .comment-meta .commentmetadata -->
			</div>
			<div class="clear"></div>
			<div class="comment-content">
									
				<p>I work with the homeless mentally ill. The homeless have almost no choice but to eat at long food lines, which many mentally ill can&#8217;t handle, or from which they have been excluded for behavioral issues. Some fast food places have started accepting food stamps, after program rules changed. Money of any kind doesn&#8217;t go far at those places. Some bagged food programs don&#8217;t allow participation unless you can prove you have resources to store and cook it.<br />
    Years ago when I worked at a day center for them that did not a food program, Panera in San Diego would donate huge bags of day-old product that went a long ways towards filling the need. </p>
<p>I&#8217;ve never forgotten that.</p>
			</div>
			<div class="reply"><a class='comment-reply-link' href='/panera-bread-ceo-learns-poverty-firsthand-week-poverty/?replytocom=129023#respond' onclick='return addComment.moveForm("comment-129023", "129023", "respond", "16180")'>Reply</a></div><!-- .reply -->
		</div><!-- #comment-##  -->

	</li><!-- #comment-## -->
	<li id="comment-129017">
		<div  class="comment even thread-even depth-1 comment-wrap" >
			<div class="comment-avatar"><img alt='' src='http://0.gravatar.com/avatar/0652d64d2b1a9993fc91bd27b089120b?s=45&amp;d=identicon&amp;r=G' class='avatar avatar-45 photo' height='45' width='45' /></div>
			<div class="author-comment">
				<cite class="fn">diane</cite> 				<div class="comment-meta commentmetadata"><a href="http://aattp.org/panera-bread-ceo-learns-poverty-firsthand-week-poverty/#comment-129017">	September 26, 2013 at 7:44 pm</a></div><!-- .comment-meta .commentmetadata -->
			</div>
			<div class="clear"></div>
			<div class="comment-content">
									
				<p>It just kills me when people talk about abuse of the food stamps program, or that they see people buying cigarettes, alcohol, etc., or selling them for cash to buy drugs. They&#8217;re either lying through their teeth, or referencing something from 30 years ago.</p>
<p>First of all, food stamps are not &#8220;stamps&#8221; &#8211; there are no separate pieces of paper. You get a debit card that has set amount on it. You can&#8217;t sell or trade anything.</p>
<p>Second of all, food stamps will not buy cigarettes or alcohol. They also cannot be used to buy toilet paper, paper towels, diapers, baby bottles, soap, shampoo, aspirin, cough medicine, band-aids, and anything else in your bathroom. You can&#8217;t buy anything for the kitchen that isn&#8217;t food. You can&#8217;t buy stamps. You can&#8217;t buy school supplies for your kids. You can&#8217;t get your worn out shoes repaired. You can&#8217;t put gas in your car or pay for a bus pass. You can&#8217;t go to the laundrymat.</p>
<p>SNAP is for an emergency, and is food, only. You can&#8217;t live on it. Yet we have millions of people who are forced to try to live on it, through no fault of their own.</p>
<p>I always wonder why people who want to stop the SNAP program think it&#8217;s okay to end a program that millions depend on because of a few bad apples. I wonder how many of them  also claim we can&#8217;t end gun rights because of a few &#8220;bad apples&#8221;&#8230;</p>
			</div>
			<div class="reply"><a class='comment-reply-link' href='/panera-bread-ceo-learns-poverty-firsthand-week-poverty/?replytocom=129017#respond' onclick='return addComment.moveForm("comment-129017", "129017", "respond", "16180")'>Reply</a></div><!-- .reply -->
		</div><!-- #comment-##  -->

