	<ul class="children">
	<li id="comment-129019">
		<div  class="comment even depth-2 comment-wrap" >
			<div class="comment-avatar"><img alt='' src='http://0.gravatar.com/avatar/0652d64d2b1a9993fc91bd27b089120b?s=45&amp;d=identicon&amp;r=G' class='avatar avatar-45 photo' height='45' width='45' /></div>
			<div class="author-comment">
				<cite class="fn">diane</cite> 				<div class="comment-meta commentmetadata"><a href="http://aattp.org/panera-bread-ceo-learns-poverty-firsthand-week-poverty/#comment-129019">	September 26, 2013 at 8:01 pm</a></div><!-- .comment-meta .commentmetadata -->
			</div>
			<div class="clear"></div>
			<div class="comment-content">
									
				<p>If you have $6 to spend and have to feed your kids, what will you spend it on? (It also depends on where you live. Food is more expensive in Los Angeles and Honolulu than it is in Kansas City or Fargo.) Fresh fruit and vegetables cost more than processed food, unfortunately. Buy two pound of apples and you&#8217;ve used up half the allotment right there. Whereas you can get maybe six boxes of mac &amp; cheese on sale and a pack of hot dogs, and you&#8217;ve got dinners for six days. A box of healthy cereal can cost upwards of $5, while a box of sugar flakes will go on sale for $2. You can get two and feed your kids breakfast for a week. Snacks? Two bags of store-brand potato chips for the price of one, or a pint of generic ice cream on sale for $2.00, versus a box of granola bars or fresh fruit sorbet for $5 each. (Poor children deserve a treat, too.) Fresh fish for $3 a pound (and how much fish do you get per person with that?) vs a bag of frozen fish sticks for $2.</p>
<p>Is it any wonder that poor people are sometimes so unhealthy? Bad food is cheap food, but at least cheap food can put on the table.</p>
			</div>
			<div class="reply"><a class='comment-reply-link' href='/panera-bread-ceo-learns-poverty-firsthand-week-poverty/?replytocom=129019#respond' onclick='return addComment.moveForm("comment-129019", "129019", "respond", "16180")'>Reply</a></div><!-- .reply -->
