	<li id="comment-128949">
		<div  class="comment odd alt thread-even depth-1 comment-wrap" >
			<div class="comment-avatar"><img alt='' src='http://0.gravatar.com/avatar/6d177198bd915438d8282ab61c38a174?s=45&amp;d=identicon&amp;r=G' class='avatar avatar-45 photo' height='45' width='45' /></div>
			<div class="author-comment">
				<cite class="fn">Geneva</cite> 				<div class="comment-meta commentmetadata"><a href="http://aattp.org/panera-bread-ceo-learns-poverty-firsthand-week-poverty/#comment-128949">	September 26, 2013 at 12:03 pm</a></div><!-- .comment-meta .commentmetadata -->
			</div>
			<div class="clear"></div>
			<div class="comment-content">
									
				<p>I currently work part-time (15 to 18 hours per week) and get food stamps.  After 2 years of unemployment, the last 6 months of it without any unemployment benefits, I&#8217;m glad to have a part-time job.  I get $50.00 per month for food. Yes, you read that correctly. $50 a month for a family of one.  That&#8217;s roughly $1.67 budget per day for food.  Can I get enough healthy food (fresh fruits and veggies; good cuts of meat) to last me a month? Nope. Luckily I stocked up on soup and baking supplies (for bread, not cookies and cakes) before they cut my food stamps from $200 a month to $50 a month.  I don&#8217;t know why they cut it, they won&#8217;t tell me and they won&#8217;t raise it.  I&#8217;m glad for the $50 a month but not being able to afford healthy food sucks when you already have weight issues as well has high blood pressure.  I dare all of you who think people who collect food stamps are lazy to live on $1.67 a day or $50 a month for food and stay healthy &#8211; NO JUNK FOOD!   No eating out. No stopping at a gas station for a snack. No Starbucks. Purchase enough food to last you 2 or 3 meals a day (healthy meals) with only $50.</p>
			</div>
