	<li id="comment-128948">
		<div  class="comment odd alt thread-odd thread-alt depth-1 comment-wrap" >
			<div class="comment-avatar"><img alt='' src='http://0.gravatar.com/avatar/6e2396ce05bf049218c226f9d570ab9b?s=45&amp;d=identicon&amp;r=G' class='avatar avatar-45 photo' height='45' width='45' /></div>
			<div class="author-comment">
				<cite class="fn">Bill Wallace</cite> 				<div class="comment-meta commentmetadata"><a href="http://aattp.org/panera-bread-ceo-learns-poverty-firsthand-week-poverty/#comment-128948">	September 26, 2013 at 11:52 am</a></div><!-- .comment-meta .commentmetadata -->
			</div>
			<div class="clear"></div>
			<div class="comment-content">
									
				<p>We do need to ensure that people have the resources to feed their families properly. An honest living wage would help. Certainly cutting food programs is not helpful. And those folks who oppose SNAP will scream the loudest when they find themselves in hard times with no help.<br />
I am glad that he did this because it shows how difficult that it is. But it does not mean that you have to compromise a healthy diet, you just must be careful in what you buy and how you use it. It does take more than week to learn how to do it.</p>
<p>I have taken the challenge of feeding my family for the amount that you get in SNAP benefits. And it is possible. We have been doing it for several months now. Yes, I buy steak regularly, but it’s what you do with it that matters. First I buy clearance meat (except chicken) which costs about the same or less per pound as hamburger. This meat isn&#8217;t going be dodgey for at least a week more, but they need to sell it or toss it. Even salmon can be purchased for less than regularly priced hamburger meat which also occasionally makes it into the sale bin.</p>
<p>Put a good spice rub on the steak, broil it and then slice it thin. Serve it on $1.49 day old sub rolls with a 99 cent packet of sautéed frozen peppers and cheese with a side Caesar salad. Or slice it up and make a stir fry with packets of frozen veggies. Serve the stir fry over Ramen or rice. Or make it into Pad Thai or a curry. You can make our own Pad Thai or curry sauce for almost nothing using the ingredients in your pantry rather buying a $5.00 bottle of it. Home made enchiladas are another possibility to stretch the meat into many servings. You just fed an army of teenagers steak in a balanced meal for about $1.00 to $1.50 per serving. And they eat it quickly. But when my son or daughter goes over to their houses, all they have is frozen food and they complain that they have nothing good to eat. Their parents complain about how expensive their food budget is. Frozen veggies are the exception to the no frozen food rule since they prevent waste from spoilage of fresh veggies. Real cooking makes the difference.</p>
<p>Never buy soda; it&#8217;s just expensive water. Use the powered drink mix, add a splash of club soda when you pour it and you have the same thing for a fraction of the cost. You don&#8217;t have to give up coffee. Just buy the big bargain tin of it for less than the cost of a bag of designer coffee. It is good coffee. Save the morning&#8217;s leftovers to make iced coffee.Saved coffee, a dollop of cheap ice cream and ice in a blender makes those $5.00 frozen drinks that we are all fond of.  </p>
<p>You can eat “luxury” foods on a budget, if you use them correctly. Good food equals good nutrition, something that isn’t found in the frozen food or hamburger helper diet. Good nutrition creates benefits like better grades and better health. Be creative, eat well and don’t spend a fortune on food.</p>
<p>PS You can make a lot of lobster rolls or salad or a huge lobster pizza from a couple of sale lobster tails. Again at a low cost per serving.</p>
			</div>
			<div class="reply"><a class='comment-reply-link' href='/panera-bread-ceo-learns-poverty-firsthand-week-poverty/?replytocom=128948#respond' onclick='return addComment.moveForm("comment-128948", "128948", "respond", "16180")'>Reply</a></div><!-- .reply -->
		</div><!-- #comment-##  -->

